{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626462"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:37:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:37:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17074"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17074"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.38,0,0.28,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77357"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9764"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17074"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5292"},{"type":"tags","id":"5297"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"9982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23156"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77357"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF-alpha) is a key pro-inflammatory cytokine involved in the pathogenesis of several autoimmune diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of TNF-alpha antagonist drugs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents TNF-alpha release from cells","Blocks TNF-alpha receptor signalling pathways","Increases TNF-alpha degradation","Binds and neutralises TNF-alpha","Reduces TNF-alpha gene transcription"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETNF-alpha antagonists work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding and neutralising TNF-alpha\u003C/strong\u003E, stopping its binding to receptors on target cells. This reduces inflammatory signalling and immune activation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese drugs do not \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent TNF-alpha release from cells\u003C/strong\u003E as they act on the cytokine after it has been released into the extracellular space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey do not \u003Cstrong\u003Eblock TNF-alpha receptor signalling pathways\u003C/strong\u003E as they act on the cytokine itself rather than affecting downstream signalling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey do not \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease TNF-alpha degradation\u003C/strong\u003E but instead bind and neutralise the cytokine directly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey do not \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduce TNF-alpha gene transcription\u003C/strong\u003E as they have no direct effect on gene expression or protein production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETNF-alpha antagonists are important biological drugs with therapeutic indications in disease such as rheumatoid arthritis, psoriasis, and inflammatory bowel disease. By neutralising excess TNF-alpha, they help control inflammation and reduce disease activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF-alpha) antagonists work by binding and neutralising TNF-alpha, preventing it from interacting with cell surface receptors.","Tumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF-alpha) antagonists drugs are used to treat autoimmune conditions like rheumatoid arthritis and inflammatory bowel disease.","Common tumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF-alpha) antagonists include adalimumab, infliximab, and etanercept."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17074"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T17:53:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T17:54:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9764"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77357"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Leve